Rating: 4
I had to review this recipe. It is GREAT!!! My husband and I love it. It is easy and has such a unique flavor. We have mashed potatoes with it which is so good with the sauce. I have only changed one thing. One day after deciding,on the spur of the moment, to have it for dinner I was unable to marinate the chops overnight. I sprayed them with olive oil and sprinkled with salt and pepper and let them sit for a few hours in the fridge. They were delicious! In fact, we thought they were better than when marinaded. I plan on having this many more times in the future.

Rating: 4
Delicious and very easy, though it takes a while to reduce the brine and especially the accompanying barbeque sauce. I used 1.5-inch chops and cooked them for 20 minutes. I had plenty of time to kill while the barbeque sauce was cooking down.

Rating: 4
I pulled this recipe when it first appeared in Bon Appetit, and it has be THE summer pork chop recipe ever since. I have even done chicken breasts with the same ingredients (don't marinate as long as the pork) and they were just as great. The sauce is very spicy but our guests always love it!

Rating: 4
Simply fabulous. The brine really complemented the pork and kept them moist and flavourful. I made Steve Raichlen's Barbecue sauce to go with it and served it with some roasted sweet potatoes dressed with a little olive oil and lime juice. Sublime meal.

Rating: 3
Very easy marinade! I made as suggested, except with only 2 cups of water boiling. Added 2 cups of ice water to cool faster. Marinated for 4 hours. Cooked indirect on the Weber for 5 minutes / side... Super pork chops! Don't need any sauce (although I used some Stubb's Original, one of the best in the supermarket on the side). You won't be disappointed.

Rating: 4
I can't count how many times I have made this...we love it. Works well with chicken too. The sauce is the key...I double or triple it and freeze portions for quicker meals later. Served for Easter (much more fun than ham) with April, 2003 Gratin of potatoes with tarragon and cheddar.

Rating: 2
The marinade was great---brining the chops helped keep them moist and the thyme was a wonderful compliment. After I'd finished the barbecue sauce (and tasted it) I almost hated to apply it to the chops. Nobody was crazy about the barbecue sauce; it did have a smoky flavor, but otherwise was fairly bland. I'd do the marinade again, but not the barbecue sauce.

